Now all flight parameters are defined in terms of the control input, parafoil state (altitude), and constant parafoil parameters. Consequently, the following parafoil properties have to be known:


L/D(δa) – the glide ratio as a function of differential flap deflection;

σ0(δa) – the bank response to differential flap deflection at reference altitude;

Veq0 – the equivalent equilibrium gliding airspeed at zero differential flap deflection.
For a given canopy, these properties depend on the rigging angle, symmetric flap deflection, and the wing loading. The air density ρ(h) is known from the atmosphere model. If the rate of turn is measured in test drops, it can replace σ in the model presented. Using σ as an intermediate variable merely simplifies the equations.

Cohesion and separation. The principles of cohesion and separation may be implemented separately or together, by definition of a suitable control law. This rule is manifesting itself through an attractive or repulsive force acting on the parafoil based on the local flock configuration. However, this force, or action vector, cannot be directly applied to the parafoil to produce an acceleration. Therefore, it will be translated into a suitable command of left or right turn. The local flock configuration can be defined in either one of two ways:


Centroid based: position vector of the local centroid in the own-vehicle centred axes – i.e. the average position of the vehicles within the local neighbourhood, including the own vehicle;

Flockmate based: set of positions of the vehicles within the local neighbourhood in the own-vehicle centred axes
